      <h1>Warning signs &amp; risk factors</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Things to notice — in yourself or in someone you care about —
        and the factors that raise or lower the risk of gambling harm.
        Noticing is not diagnosing. Wherever you are on the spectrum,
        help is available whenever you want it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Things to notice — and why they happen</h2>
      <p>
        For most people, gambling is just entertainment. But for some,
        it can start to cause harm. The good news is that harm rarely
        appears overnight. There are usually signs along the way —
        things you can notice in yourself or in someone you love.
      </p>
      <p>
        This page is here to help you notice, not to scare you. Think of
        it as a gentle guide, not a test you can pass or fail.
      </p>
      <p>A few things to keep in mind as you read:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Gambling problems sit on a spectrum.</strong> They
          range from "no problem at all," to "a few signs and some
          stress," to a diagnosable gambling disorder. Most people who
          run into trouble are somewhere in the middle, not at the far
          end.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Harm can happen before there is any "disorder."</strong>
          A person does not need to meet every clinical criterion to be
          hurt by gambling. Lost sleep, money worries, and strained
          relationships count.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Noticing signs is not a diagnosis.</strong> Only a
          trained professional can diagnose a gambling disorder. Seeing
          a few signs simply means it may be worth a closer, kinder
          look.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Wherever you are on the spectrum, things can get better, and
        help is available whenever you want it.
      </p>

      <h2>Warning signs in yourself</h2>
      <p>
        If you have been wondering about your own gambling, that
        question alone is worth taking seriously — and gently. Here are
        some common signs, grouped by what they tend to affect. You may
        notice none, a few, or many. There is no magic number.
      </p>

      <h3>How you think and act (behavioral)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You think about gambling a lot — past bets, the next bet,
          where to get money to play.</li>
        <li>You feel you need to bet more money, or bet more often, to
          get the same excitement.</li>
        <li>You keep gambling to win back money you have lost ("chasing
          losses").</li>
        <li>You have tried to cut back or stop, but found you couldn't
          (NCPG, 2026).</li>
        <li>You sometimes hide how much you gamble, or play in secret.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Money (financial)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You are borrowing money, selling things, or using money
          meant for bills to gamble.</li>
        <li>Bills are going unpaid, or savings are shrinking, because
          of gambling.</li>
        <li>You notice money or valuables going missing and can't fully
          explain it.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Remember: how much you win or lose does <strong>not</strong>
        decide whether gambling is a problem. Gambling can affect your
        relationships, mood, or health even if the dollar amounts seem
        small (NCPG, 2026).
      </p>

      <h3>How you feel (emotional and mental health)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You feel restless or irritable when you try to cut down or
          stop.</li>
        <li>You gamble to escape stress, sadness, anxiety, or other
          hard feelings.</li>
        <li>You feel guilt, shame, anxiety, or low mood connected to
          gambling.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Your life and relationships (social, work, school)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Gambling is causing tension or arguments with people close
          to you.</li>
        <li>You are pulling back from friends, family, or activities
          you used to enjoy.</li>
        <li>Gambling is getting in the way of work, school, or
          responsibilities at home.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If several of these feel familiar, it does not mean something
        is "wrong with you." It means gambling may be costing you more
        than it gives back — and that is something you can do something
        about. A short, private self-check (below) can help you see
        where you stand.
      </p>

      <h2>Warning signs in someone you care about</h2>
      <p>
        When you are worried about a partner, family member, or friend,
        the signs can be harder to see — people often try to hide
        gambling, especially when they feel ashamed. You may notice the
        <em>effects</em> before you ever see the gambling itself.
      </p>

      <h3>Behavioral</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>They seem preoccupied with gambling, or always seem to be
          planning the next bet.</li>
        <li>They are secretive about their phone, money, or where they
          have been.</li>
        <li>They have promised to cut back, but the gambling continues.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Financial</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Money or valuables go missing, or there are unexplained
          loans and debts.</li>
        <li>Bills are unpaid, or they keep asking to borrow money —
          sometimes urgently.</li>
        <li>You find betting apps, receipts, or accounts you didn't
          know about.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Emotional and mental health</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>They seem more irritable, anxious, withdrawn, or down than
          usual.</li>
        <li>Their mood seems to rise and fall with wins and losses.</li>
        <li>They express guilt, hopelessness, or talk about being "in
          too deep."</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social, work, and school</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>They are missing work, school, or family events.</li>
        <li>They are pulling away from people, or relationships are
          growing tense.</li>
        <li>Friends or family members have started to worry too.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Noticing these signs does not mean you have to confront anyone
        or have all the answers. It can simply be the start of a caring
        conversation — and a reason to learn what support is out there.
        Support exists for <strong>loved ones</strong>, too, not only
        for the person who gambles.
      </p>

      <h2>A note on safety</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling problems can weigh heavily on a person's mind, and
        research shows they carry a higher-than-average risk of
        suicidal thoughts. A large review of 107 studies found that,
        among people with gambling problems, about 1 in 3 reported
        suicidal thoughts at some point in their lives, and people with
        gambling problems were roughly twice as likely to report such
        thoughts as people without them (Kristensen et al., 2024).
      </p>
      <p>
        We share this not to frighten anyone, but because it matters
        and help is real. If you or someone you care about is thinking
        about suicide or in emotional crisis, you can reach the
        <strong>988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</strong> any time —
        call, text, or chat <a href="tel:988">988</a>. You don't have to
        be sure it's "serious enough." Reaching out is always okay.
      </p>
      <p>
        For gambling-specific support, you can also contact the
        <strong>National Problem Gambling Helpline</strong> at
        <a href="tel:18006973738">1-800-MY-RESET (1-800-697-3738)</a>
        — call or text.
      </p>

      <h2>What raises the risk?</h2>
      <p>
        No single thing "causes" a gambling problem, and having a risk
        factor does not mean a problem is coming. Risk factors simply
        make problems somewhat more likely — and understanding them can
        take away some of the self-blame. Researchers sort them into
        things about the <strong>person</strong> and things about the
        <strong>environment</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>Individual factors</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Starting young.</strong> People who begin gambling at
          an early age are more likely to develop problems later
          (NCPG, 2026; Dowling et al., 2017). Teens and young adults
          are at higher risk than older adults.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>An early big win.</strong> A large win early on can
          leave a strong impression and make gambling feel more
          rewarding or "winnable" than it really is (ICRG, 2026).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Impulsivity and sensation-seeking.</strong> A tendency
          to act on impulse or to chase excitement is linked to higher
          risk (Dowling et al., 2017).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Family history.</strong> Having a parent or close
          relative with gambling, alcohol, or drug problems raises the
          odds — through both genes and environment (NCPG, 2026).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Other mental-health or substance-use conditions.</strong>
          Depression, anxiety, and alcohol or drug use often occur
          alongside gambling problems and can increase risk (Dowling et
          al., 2017; Kristensen et al., 2024).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Certain beliefs about luck and odds.</strong> Many
          people hold mistaken ideas like the <strong>gambler's
          fallacy</strong> (thinking a loss "must" be followed by a
          win) or the <strong>illusion of control</strong> (feeling
          that skill, a system, or a ritual can sway a game of chance).
          These beliefs can keep someone playing and chasing losses.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Environmental and access factors</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Easy access.</strong> When gambling is always
          available — for example, betting apps on a phone — it is
          easier to gamble more often, with fewer natural breaks
          (ICRG, 2026).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Speed and "always-on" features.</strong> Faster
          games, and features like live "in-play" or micro-betting,
          give quick, repeated outcomes that can make it harder to
          stop (NCPG, 2026; ICRG, 2026).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Heavy marketing.</strong> Frequent ads and
          promotions can normalize gambling and nudge people to play
          more.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Financial stress.</strong> Money pressure can make
          the hope of a big win feel especially appealing, which can
          deepen a cycle of chasing losses.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A note on fairness: certain products and settings carry more
        risk than others, but the <em>opportunity</em> to gamble is not
        the same as the <em>cause</em> of a problem — much as a store
        that sells alcohol does not, by itself, cause alcohol problems
        (NCPG, 2026).
      </p>

      <h2>What helps protect people?</h2>
      <p>
        Just as some things raise risk, others are linked to lower
        risk. Protective factors are an area where research is still
        growing, but a few stand out — and they are things people,
        families, and communities can build on (Dowling et al., 2017).
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Accurate beliefs about odds and randomness.</strong>
          Understanding that games of chance are random — that there
          is no "due" number and no winning ritual — makes it easier
          to keep gambling in check.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Strong social connection.</strong> Supportive
          relationships, family closeness, and (for young people)
          involved, aware parents are linked to lower risk (Dowling et
          al., 2017).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Healthy ways to cope.</strong> Having other ways to
          handle stress, boredom, or hard feelings — besides gambling
          — helps.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Setting limits ahead of time.</strong> Deciding in
          advance how much time and money you'll spend, and sticking
          to it, is a simple, protective habit.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of these are guarantees. But they are reminders that risk
        is not destiny, and that small, everyday choices can make a
        real difference.
      </p>

      <h2>Take a short, private self-check</h2>
      <p>
        If anything here struck a chord — for you or someone you love —
        a brief self-check is a calm next step.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/understand-gambling/rate-your-risk"><strong>Take the
        self-check →</strong></a>
      </p>
      <p>
        It only takes a few minutes. A self-check is <strong>not</strong>
        a diagnosis — it can't tell you that you "have" a gambling
        disorder. What it <em>can</em> do is help you see where you
        stand and decide what, if anything, you'd like to do next.
      </p>
      <p>
        And whatever the result, help is available whenever you want
        it:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>National Problem Gambling Helpline:</strong>
          <a href="tel:18006973738">1-800-MY-RESET (1-800-697-3738)</a>
          — call or text for support and to connect with resources in
          your area.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>In crisis or thinking about suicide?</strong> Call,
          text, or chat <a href="tel:988">988</a> (988 Suicide &amp;
          Crisis Lifeline), available any time.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        You don't have to have it all figured out to reach out. Taking
        a look is already a step.
      </p>

